{"/service/ndnp/mdu/batch_mdu_anhinga_ver01/data/sn88065202/00340588204/1930122501/0414.xml":{"full_text":"VOLUME 54.\nFOR 1931 IN LOCAL TROOP\n22 Scouts Earn 72 Merit Badges\nThroughout Year\u2014Troop Now\nHas Forty-one Members\n26 ADVANCE IN SCOUTING\nTwenty-two first and second class\nscouts, members of Oakland Troop\nNo. 1, passed 72 merit badges, 26\nmembers of the troop advanced at\nleast one rank, one member received\nthe rank of Eagle scout, and other\nachievements for the year 1930 are\nrecorded in the annual report which\nhas just been sent to National Head\nquarters by George H. Hanst, scout\nmaster.\nThis interest in class study, coupled\nwith the two weeks\u2019 camping trip and\nparticipation in many other events\nhas made the year 1930 an important\none for the local troop.\nAt the present time there are 41\nmembers of the troop, 5 Tenderfoot\nscouts, 15 second class, and 21 first\nclass scouts. Three of the first class\nscouts are Eagle scouts and one of\nthese is Knight-Eagle, the highest\nrank any boy can obtain. Only seven\nwere removed from the troop roll\nduring the past year, and these were\ncalled away by school, work, moving\naway, ete.\nThose who advanced at least one\nrank during the past year are Eugene\nShow, Willus Hull, Leroy Stewart, J.\nB. Yutzy, to Tenderfoot; Gerald Iman,\nJack Treacy, George Kerins, Howard\nNaylor, Fred Peddicord, Carroll Cas\nteel, Kenneth Lawton, Robert Utter\nback, George Browning, to Second\nclass; Schell Hoye, James Treacy,\nGeorge Stuck, Richard Gonder, Lewis\nJones, John Meclntire and David\nWalter to First class; Robert Alt\nstetter and Richard Gonder to Star\nscout; Richard Glotfelty and Elvin\nIman to Life scout; and Ward Hine\nbaugh to Eagle.\nMerit Badges Passed\nSeventy-two merit badges were\nwon by 22 first and second class\nscouts the past year, the report\nstates. A merit badge is given that\na scout may find his life\u2019s work. Those\npassing one or more merit badges\nwere Harley Dawson, Walter Dawson,\nSchell Hoye, John Mclntire, Richard\nGlotfelty, Bernard Gonder, Richard\nGonder, Donald Stemple, Lewis\nJones, Gerald Iman, Carroll Casteel,\nRobert Altstetter, Lewis Lawton,\nHoward Rathbun, Jack Treacy, Jas.\nTreacy, Stuart Hamill, George Ker\nins, William Tillett, Elvin Iman, Ken\nneth Lawton, Ward Hinebaugh.\nJames Treacy passed the highest\nnumber with 8, fvhile Robert Altstett\ner and Richard Glotfelty each passed\n6.\nBadges were won in bookbinding,\nfirst aid, physical development, fire\nmanship, camping, masonery, reading,\npathfinding, handicraft, electricity,\npublic health, personal health, life\nsaving, swimming, plumbing, bird\nstudy, civics, carpentry, leathercraft,\nfirst aid to animals, pioneering,\nblacksmithing.\nFive over-night hikes with an aver\nage attendance of 15, and eight day\nhikes with an attendance of 20, were\ntaken throughout the year; the troop\nparticipated in civic parades, planted\ntrees for the Civic club, held a public\nprogram during Anniversary Week,\nand helped in community enterprises.\nAn average of 34 boys spent two\nweeks in the scout camp on Deep\nCreek Lake.\nA public program for the scouts,,\ntheir parents and friends is being\nplanned for Anniversary Week\niliary to the troop are the Troop com\nmittee, the Court of Honor and the\nLadies\u2019 auxiliary.\n\u2014-\u2014\u2014O.__\u2014_\nCoasting Hours and Coasting\nStreets Designated by Mayor\nSpecial hours for coasting, and\nspecial streets upon which the chil\ndren may do their coasting have been\ndesignated by Grover C. Stemple,\nmayor of Oakland.\nPennington street and Fifth street\nwill be used for coasting and the\nhours during the Christmas holidays\nwill be from 2 to 9 p. m. After the\nholidays the hours will be from 4:30\nto 9.\nThere will be a watchman placed at\nintersections to see that the children\nare protected from automobile traffic.\nParents are asked to impress upon\ntheir children the danger of coasting\nany place except on the streets desig\nnated, so that all danger of accidents\ncan be avoided.\nTHE REPUBLICAN\nBLAZE DESTROYS SUMMER\nRESIDENCE AT DEER PARK\nA. T. Watson Home, Adjoining\nDeer Park Hotel, Burns\nFire of undetermined origin early\nFriday morning entirely destroyed\nthe large frame summer dwelling of\nA. T. Watson, at Deer Park. As far\nas can be learned the blaze started\nabout 3 a. m., but was not discovered\nuntil the flames had gained great\nheadway, and attempts to save the\nbuilding and furnishings were use\nless.\nThe home, during winter months,\nwas unoccupied, but was looked after\nby Mr. Jankey, of Deer Park, who\nlived nearby. It contained approxi\nmately forty rooms and was valued at\nmore than $30,000.\nIt was used as a summer home for\nthe family of Mr. Watson, former\ncoal operators of Fairmont, W. Va.\nThe dwelling adjoined the famous\nDeer Park hotel property. The loss\nis partly covered by insurance.\ne e\nENTRIES FOR CHRISTMAS\nLIGHTING CONTEST CLOSED\nJudges Will Make Rounds Every\nNight Until New Year\u2019s Night\n\u2018Twas the night before Christmas,\nand the outdoors, bright with Christ\nmas light, were awaiting the anniver\nsary of the birth of the Child Jesus.\u201d\nThat will be the message Oakland will\nsend to the heavens tonight, when\nscores of beautifully lighted and deco\nrated homes will begin to gleam with\nthe tiny jewels of colored lamps,\nformed into countless novel decora\ntions. Nearly every one of these\nhomes will be entered in the Rotary\nClub\u2019s outdoor Christmas lighting and\ndecorating contest, entries to which\nclosed Wednesday. Cash prizes, total\ning $25.00 will be distributed to own\ners of the best lighted and decorated\nhomes, when judges have made their\nrounds during the Christinas week.\nEvery. night until New Year\u2019s\nnight judges will make their rounds,\non foot and by automobile, so that\nevery house entered in the Rotary\nClub\u2019s contest will be thoroughly in\nspected and judged from every angle,\nand the prize-wirging homes an\nnounced in the next issue of this\nnewspaper. Scarcely a street is with\nout several lighted and decorated\nhomes this year, and the sponsors of\nthe contest are well pleased with the\nsuccess of the contest, and the Christ\nmas spirit that has resulted.\nEach night until New Year\u2019s, lights\nshould be kept burning in all homes\nentered in the Rotary Club\u2019s contest,\nso judges will have an opportunity to\nmake a thorough inspection. Every\none who has entered the contest by\nfilling out blanks printed in this news\npaper, may feel sure his home will\nnot be missed, and that it has an op\nportunity to win one of the prizes, if\nlighted each night until 11 o\u2019clock, as\nno judging will be done after that\nhour.\nRl s s\nAnnual Band Concert to be Held\non December Twenty-Eighth\nIn order to observe the improve\nment in the Gilbert-Brown Boys\u2019 band\nfrom year to year since its organiza\ntion in 1927, the fourth annual con\ncert of the band will be held in the\nMaryland theatre on Sunday evening,\nDecember 28, at 8:30 o\u2019clock.\nThe entertainment will be held im\nmediately after the services in the\nvarious Qakland churches. Special\nties on the program include vocal\nsolos by Reeves Blandford and Mrs.\nFrederick Thayer, and a baritone solo\nby Lewis Lawton. The band will\nrender a number of marches, over\ntures, waltzes, etc., under the direction\nof R. R. Gilbert, director. He will be\nassisted by Russell H. Brown.\nMr. Bernard Gonder is donating the\nuse of the Maryland theatre and no\nadmission will be charged. Mr.\nGrover Stemple, mayor, will make a\nfew remarks at the concert.\nit Yo\nIn Chicago, a butcher, held up by\nbandits in times past, pl_aced a revol\nver in his cash register, one in his ice\nchest, where he had been clocked up\nbefore and placed police dogs in his\nshot, the latter to be released by pull\ning a string. The bandits got the gun\nout of the register and locked him in\nthe cooler. There was so much frost\non the weapon that it failed to fire,\nand the two dogs, instead of grabbing\nthe bandits, being hungry, sank their\nteeth in the beef.\nAt Fairmont, station WMMN cele\nbrated its second birthday Monday by\na two-day air program.\nOAKLAND, MARYLAND, DECEMBER 25, 1930.\nPRELIMINARY RESULTS OF FARM CENSUS OF GARRETT\nCOUNTY FOR YEAR 1930 ARE GIVEN OUT BY DIRECTOR\nThe following statement, issued by\nthe Director of the Census, gives some\nof the results of the 1930 farm census\nfor Garrett county, with comparative\ndata for 1925 and 1920 for selected\nitems. The 1930 figures are prelimi\nnary and subject to correction:\ni The 1930 census was taken April\n1, while the census for 1925 and 1920\nwas taken January 1.\nGarrett County Farms\nNumber of farms, 1930, 1,839; 1925,\n'1,974; 1920, 1,810.\nAcreage of all land in farms, 1930,\n241,248; 1925, 238,960; 1920, 244,754.\nAverage acres per farm, 1930,\n131.2; 1925, 121.1; 1920, 135.2.\nValue of land and buildings, 1930,\n$8,093,452; 1925, $8,415,550; 1920.\n$8,466,103.\nValue, land alone, 1930, $4,766,229;\n1925, $5,478,602; 1920, $5,805,751.\nValue of buildings, 1930, $3,327,223;\n1925, $2,936,948; 1920, $2,660,352.\nValue of dwellings alone, 1930, sl,-\n771,097. Value for 1925 and 1920 not\ngiven.\nValue of implements and machin\nery, 1930, $785,477; 1925, $726,852;\ni 1920,.5728,957.\nAverage value of land and build\nings per farm, 1930, $4,401; 1925,\n$4,263; 1920, 4,677; per acre value,\nTRY-OUTS FOR DRAMATIC\nORGANIZATION COMPLETED'\nOfficers Chosen for Club; Blanch\nRidder is President\nFor the past two weeks Miss Koch-}\nenderfer has been conducting try-outs\nfor the high school Dramatic Club.\nThese have now been completed and\nthe club is ready for work. i\nJuniors and seniors only-}are\u2018-eli-\u2018\ngible for membership in this club.\nThe officers elected by the club are as\nfollows: By e\nPresident, Blanche Ridder; vice\n\u2018president, David Walter; seoretary\ufb02\nRichard Glotfelty; treasurer,. Mona\nO\u2019Brien. 5\nMembers were chosen as follows:\nOlive Gnegy, Gladys Aronhalt, Kath\nleen Jessee, Anna Bell Stemple, Wil\nma Moomaw, Carroll Casteel, Betty\nBroadwater, Mary Lynn Mclntire, Lo\ngan Weber, Ralph Turney, Lewis\nWildman, Donald Moore, Clara Belle\nHamill, Richard Roy, Elvin .Iman,\nEugene Nordeck, Wayne Hamilton,\nWayne Fitzwater, Wellington Welch,\nEdwin Michael, Hasaleah Yutzy, Vir\nginia Giessman, Jessie Moon, Regi\nnald Ford, Anna Mae Sowers, Harley\nDawson, Robert Bowen, Joe Glotfelty,\nEdward Hinebaugh, Helen Shaffer,\nLloyd Bowers, Donald Stemple, Allen\nKelly, Joe Sollars.\nO \u2014ee\nEntertainment Given At St.\nPeter\u2019s School\nOn Saturday afternoon a delight\nful entertainment was given at St.\nPeter\u2019s School Hall, Oakland.\nThe school children sang four\nChristmas choruses.\nThe pupils of the piano class played\nsolos. These included Bettie Broad\nwater, Cecelia Kerins, Virginia Giess\nman, Mae Jean Stediford, Frances\nFilsinger, Bond Weber, Stella Corliss,\nJane Fraley, Geneva Murphy, Estelle\nTreacy, Margaret Rudy, Jack Web\ner, Jimmie Hessen, Genevieve Sween\ney, Pauline Wolfe, Peggy McComas,\nBetsy Weber, Frances Riley, Mamie\nTreacy, Miriam O\u2019Donnell, and Dolo\nres Kerins.\nThe rhythm class danced some folk\ndances, sang songs and played instru\nments. These youngsters were Billy\nStemple, Billy Treacy, Bobbie Rudy,\nJohn Murphy, Maurice Davis, John\nGrant, Leo Treacy, Jimmie Hessen,\nJack Riley, Bernard Cogley, Esther\nLou Davis, Nell Broadwater Carol\nWeber, Martha Ann Dixon, Betty\nKeller, Miriam O\u2019Donnell, Mamie\nTreacy, Peggy McComas and Betsy\nWeber.\nP VY\nDIED.\nMRS. EMMA ELIZABETH ROSS\nMrs. Emma Elizabeth Ross, wife of\nAlbert G. Ross, deputy clerk of the\nGarrett County Circuit Court, died at\nthe family home in East Oakland this\n(Wednesday) morning at 11:00 o\u2019clock\nfollowing a long and painful illness.\nMrs. Ross was born July 15, 1873, the\ndaughter of the late Andrew Jackson\nRhodes, of the North Glade section of\nGarrett county. Mrs. Ross is survived\nby a daughter, Lois, besides her hus\nband. The funeral of Mrs. Ross will\noccury on Friday, the hour yet to be\u2018\nnamed.\n1930, $33.55; 1925, $35.22;1920, $34.59.\nThe number operated by owners in\n1930 was 1,630; by managers, 11; by\ntenants, 198, as against owner-opera\ntion in 1920, 1,648; managers, 22; ten\nants, 140.\nThere are 6 farms under 3 acres;\n52, 3 to 9 acres; 73, 10 to 19 acres,\n245, 2v to 49 acres; 500, 50 to 99\nacres; 536, 100 to 174 acres; 260, 175\nto 259 acres; 132, 260 to 499 acres;\n29, 500 to 999 acres; 6, 1,000 acres\nand over. The farm livestock for 1930\nconsisted of 3\u00a755 horses; 116 mules;\n17,564 cattle; 6,356 milk cows; 3,612\nhogs; 101,065 chickens.\nProduction of selected crops taken\nin the 1930 census covered the harvest\nof the year preceding\u2014l929\u2014and\nconsisted of the following:\nIn bushels: Corn harvested for\ngrain, 181,152; 1924, 92,463; 1919,\n253,244; oats threshed for grain, 331,-\n782; 1924, 341,625; 1919, 401,648.\nBuckwheat, 103,823; 1924, 90,6564;\n1919, 115,871. Wheat, 39,665; 1924,\n35,516; 1919, 82,643. Hay (tons), 32,-\n761; 1924, 32,127; 1919, 27,792. Corn\ncut for silage (tons), 14,393; 1924,\n9.459; 1919, 11,875. Potatoes (bush\nels), 210,185; 1924, 119,880; 1919,\n164,844.\n'MISS HARPER TALKS ON\nCHRISTMAS DECORATIONS\nDemonstrates Many Inexpensive\nWays of Fixing Up Home\nA very useful and informational\ndemonstration on Christmas decora\ntion was given Thursday afternoon in\nthe high school auditorium by Miss\nBetty Harper. Miss Harper repre\nsents the Home Service Department\nof the Monongahela West Penn Com\npany and is well known by the women\nof this eommunity for her interesting\nwork. J\nThe demonstration showed many. in.:\nteresting as well as inexpensive ways\n|to decorate your home for Christmas.\nThe small. pig-tail socket played an\nimportant part in the demonstration.\nIt was used in the center of three po\ninsettias which were placed in a flower\nerock. This lighted flower arrange\nment would look lovely at the side of\na fire-place. Apig-tail socket was in\nserted into an inflated balloon, three\nof which were used in a cluster with\ngreen paper holly leaves. This lighted\nornament would be very effective\nhanging from an archway or center\nlight.\nI At the gonclusion of the demonstra\nltion, Miss Harper showed the girls\na number of photographs taken in\nhomes which had been decorated ac\nlcording to the suggestions given in\nthe lecture. Following this Miss Har\nper answered many questions asked\nby the girls concerning the arrange\nment of certain decorations in which\nthey were especially interested.\n\u2014Oakland, The Acorn.\nPR |W\u2014 A\nNews of Oakland High School\nThe Christmas round table under\nthe direction of Miss Monna Bland\nwas presented last Friday evening,\nDecember 19. The Christmas spirit\niwas portrayed throughout the pro\ngram. Oakland Grammar School dra\nmatized the Yule log customs of old\nEngland, the Scandinavian Christmas,\nthe French Christmas and the Negro\nChristmas. The High School glee club\nended the program with a \u201ccandle\nlight procession\u201d of America.\nMiss Betty Harper, of the Home\nService Department of the Mononga\nhela West Penn Company, gave an in\nteresting as well as beneficial demon\nstration of interior decorating for\nChristmrs.\nMiss 'Harper\u2019s demonstration was\ncentered around different uses of the\nlighted pig tail socket used in the\ncenter of poinsettias, balloons, bells,\npine cones and other decoration.\nThis demonstration was given be\nfore a large group of high school girls\nThursday afternoon at 2:45.\nThe members of the O. H. S. fac\nlulty, who will spend the holidays out\nof the city are: Miss Mary Thomas,\nGrafton, W. Va.; Miss Edna Kraft,\ni\u00dfaltimore; Miss Monna Bland, Mor\nsgantown; Miss Martha Engle, at her\ni home near Grantsville; Miss Margaret\u2018\nKochenderfer, Elkins; Mr. Foster\nSpeicher, Grantsville; Mr. Ervin S.\n'Smith, Portland, Indiana; Mr. W. K.\nWhitcraft, White Hall, Md.; Mr.\nS.. Warner, Bellaire, O 0.; Mr. W. W.\nJenkins, Baltimore.\nOther members of the faculty will\nremain at their homes in Oakland\nduring the holiday season.\nMISSING YOUTH IS FOUND\nAT THE HOME OF FRIENDS\ni\nHarcy Moon Discovered Friday\nNight Near Bloomington\nHarry Lester Moon, 16-year-old\nson of J. E. Moon, Cumberland, who\nwas reported as missing from the\nhome of his grandmother, Mrs. Zack\nMoon, Bloomington, this county, since\nlast Monday, was found Friday night\nat the home of a friend, near Bloom\nington.\nThe youth took his dog and gun last\nMonday to go hunting and it was\nfeared that he was lost or had met\nwith an accident. The boy was un\naware that his absence had caused\nany alarm. His older brother, Charles\nMoon, was drowned in the Potomac\nriver on July 30, 1929.\nThe boy is now at the home of his\ngrandmother.\ne e e\nROAD COMMITTEEMAN HAS\nCONFERENCE WITH MR. UHL\nMr. McCullough Informs People\nOutcome of Meeting With\nState Roads Commission\nMr. J. W. McCullough, of Friends\nville, representing a committee of cit\nizens of Garrett county appointed at\na recent gathering held in Oakland\nwhere the feasibility of going into\nroad improvement work in all sec\ntions of the county during the com\ning summer and this manner reliev\ning to some extent the unemployment\nsituation, was chosen at a recent\nmeeting of the committee to confer\nwith Roads Chairman Uhl\nMr. McCullough, as he states in the\nletter following, had a meeting with\nthe chairman of the Commission as\nexplained in the communication to\nThe Republican published herewith:\nTo the Editor of The Republican.\nAs I was selected to negotiate with\nMr. Uhl for a meeting with the com\nmittee to determine what we could\nwork out for the betterment of our\n.read congditions, I submit to you an\narticle which I 'wish:you would plaee\nin your paper this week that will let\nthe people know what has developed\nup to this time as I feel a great many\nof our citizens are anxious to keep in\ntouch with what is going on.\nAt the committee meeting at the\nCourt House, Saturday, December 13,\nI was instructed by the committee to\nwrite Mr. G. Clinton Uhl, chairman, a\nletter for a meeting with him and the\nAttorney General to see if it would\nbe legal to take part of the State\nfunds to pay interest on the proposed\nbond issue. I received a reply from\nMr. Uhl saying he had taken the mat\nter up again with the Assistant At\n\u2018torney General and he advised Mr.\nUhl that after looking the matter up\nmore carefully it would be legal to\nuse the road funds to pay interest on\nthe bond issue.\nI had the pleasure of meeting Mr.\nUhl last Friday evening in the Fort\n\u2018Cumberland Hotel in Cumberland and\n\u2018he told me that it would be impossible\nto have a meeting with the Commis\nsion until after the first of the year\nas the Commission would not meet\nduring the holidays, and as this is a\nquestion that he wanted the full\nstate board to pass on, he thought the\nproper time and place for the meet\ning would be in the State Roads Com\nmission office in Baltimore the first\nweek the Legislature convenes.\nMr. Uhl and I talked some about\nthe bonding of the county and he said\nhe would not assume full responsibil\nity, and the matter will have to be\nsettled before the members of the\nCommission.\nPersonally I feel that it would be\nonly fair to the county to let the\ncounty settle the matter to suit the\nconditions and needs. Our county tax\nrate is SI.BO and with the/ State tax\nrate of 25 cents, makes a total tax\nrate of $2.05 on each SIOO of valua\ntion, and with the business depression\nevery reasonable effort should be\nmade to reduce this rate while this\ndepression lasts.\nThe dirt roads of our county are\nmostly of tough clay material and we\nhave the hardest freezing in the win\nter of any county in the State. When\nthe frost leaves the ground the water\nremains in the clay and the results\nare you cannot use motor vehicles on\nour dirt roads to advantage more that\nsix months of the year, and that sea\nson is not regular. Some counties\nmay be differently situated and not so\nurgently in need of roads. Let them\nwait on the regular appropriation.\nThis should be left to the people of\nthe various counties of the State to\nbetter their own conditions.\nI had published in The Republican\n(Please turn to Page Eight)\nNUMBER 45.\n_!Approximately Fifty Families\nWill Be Presented With Boxzes\nFor Christmas Season\ne\nROTARIANS GIVE TREAT\nWith all civic organizations co\noperating with the public health\nnurse during the Christmas season,\nin fixing up boxes and baskets for\nthe needy, approximately fifty fami\nlies will be taken care of this year.\nIn addition to this many individuals\nare sending out presents with best\nwishes for the new year, and the Oak\ni land Rotary club gave a special treat\nto all children Wednesday afternoon\nlbeneath the Community Christmas\ntree.\nCash donations received by Mrs.\nFahey, public health nurse, included\n$25 from the Rotary club, $2 from Mr.\nM Jarboe, $3 from Mrs. Louis\n{Bush, and $1 from an unknown\n}source. \u201cNone of the money has\nbeen used yet,\u201d Mrs. Fahey stated,\nf\u201cas people have been donating so\n'many clothes, food, etc., that it can\nbe put to better advantage a little\nlater.\u201d\ni Organizations which have gathered\nfood, clothing and toys include the\nRotary club, the home rooms of Oak\nland High school, the Oakland troop\n|of Boy Scouts, the American Red\nCross, the Legion Auxiliary, church\nsocieties, fraternal bodies, the Sew\ning Cirele for Gortner, and the Oak\n{land Civie club. Individuals have al\nso assisted in this collection and have\n\"turned over the donations to Mrs.\nFahey. Packages were wrapped and\nIdelivered on Tuesday and Wednesday.\nI \u201cMore interest is being taken this\nyear in assisting the less fortunate\nthan for some time past,\u201d Mrs. Fahey\nstated. The reason for this has been\ndiagnosed by Bruce Barton, a famous\n\u201cadvertising authority. He states: \u201cIn\n'times of business depression men and\nwomen go back to their homes, back\nto their church, vack to their ideals.\n|The Christmas season will bring out\nthe finer qualities of human nature,\n|with a desire to do something gener\nous.\u201d\n\u201cThis is evidently being the case in\nlOakland because many people have\nbecome actively engaged in distribut\nxing gifts and donating the necessities\nof life,\u201d Mrs. Fahey said. \u201cThis spir\n:it of giving will make for a happier\nChristmas.\u201d\n_\u2014_\u2014\u2014\u2014\nChristmas \u2018Cantata Presented\nLast Sunday Evening\n\u201cThe Prince of Peace,\u201d a Christ\n'mas cantata, was presented last Sun\nday evening at St. Mark\u2019s Lutheran\nlEchurch, under the direction of Dr.\nJohn G. Robinson. Approximately\n350 attended.\nSolo parts were taken by Miss Jane\nKahl, Donald R. Sincell, Dr. Robinson,\nMiss Eva Falkenstein, Miss Jane\nRobinson, William M. Frazee, Miss\nNelle Compton, Mrs. D. Edward Off\nutt; duets by Miss Kahl and Mrs.\nKarl Kahl; Miss Eva Falkenstein and\nMiss Nelle Compton; Dr. Robinson\nand Mrs. Offutt; men\u2019s quartet by\nDr. Robinson, Mr. Sincell, Mr. Frazee\nand Mr. W. H. Hinebaugh.\nMembers of the choir included Miss\nNelle Compton, Mrs. D. Edward Off\nutt, Miss Jane Robinson, Mrs. T. C.\nHinebaugh, Miss Flossie Shaffer, Miss\nJane Kahl, Miss Grace Falkenstein,\nMrs. Elinor Hoye, sopranos; Mrs.\nKarl Kahl and Miss Eva Falkenstein,\naltos; Dr. John G. Robinson, first ten\nor; George Hanst and Donald R. Sin\ncell, second tenor; William M. Frazee,\nfirst base; Wade H. Hinebaugh, T. C.\nHinebaugh, Prof. E. C. Smith, J. M.\nFalkenstein, second base. Mrs. H. A,\nLoraditch was organist.\nst it\nTruck Crashes Into Home of\nl W. H. Haenftling\nThe driver of Monheim\u2019s produce\ntruck, while enroute from Oakland to\nAccident last Friday night, seemingly\nlost control of the wheel at the curve\nin the road near the home of Sheriff\nelect W. H. Haenftling, and crashed\ninto his home, almost completely de\nmolishing the porch.\nAn apple tree was broken off in the\nyard and carried to the porch. The\ntruck was badly damaged but the two\noccupants miraculously escaped with\nonly minor injuries.\nThe truck was owned by Mon\u2018leim\u2019s\nProduce company of Uniontown, Pa.\nA check was given covering the dam\nage to Mr. Haneftling's \u2018property.","height":"26226","width":"18488"}}
